<subSubSection lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="95" pageId="1" pageNumber="94" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,1840,2011]" lastBlockId="2.[151,1437,151,465]" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="95" pageId="1" pageNumber="94">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,322,1948,1974]" pageId="1" pageNumber="94">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Schmid-Egger, 2022" authorityName="Schmid-Egger" authorityYear="2022" box="[331,543,1948,1975]" class="Insecta" family="Pompilidae" genus="Ctenagenia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="94" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="wahisi" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[331,543,1948,1975]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="94">Ctenagenia wahisi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[553,646,1949,1975]" pageId="1" pageNumber="94">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[553,646,1949,1975]" pageId="1" pageNumber="94" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
agrees in general aspects with 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Klug" baseAuthorityYear="1834" box="[1012,1176,1948,1975]" class="Insecta" family="Pompilidae" genus="Ctenagenia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="94" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vespiformis">
<emphasis box="[1012,1176,1948,1975]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="94">C. vespiformis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. It is characterized by colour pattern. T1–6 are in greater part or completely yellow, and the mesosoma is black (
<figureCitation box="[1175,1279,1984,2011]" captionStart-0="FIGURES 1–3" captionStart-1="FIGURES 4–9" captionStartId-0="1.[151,264,1590,1614]" captionStartId-1="2.[151,264,1786,1810]" captionTargetBox-0="[154,1432,919,1564]" captionTargetBox-1="[158,1432,490,1762]" captionTargetId-0="figure-317@1.[154,1432,919,1564]" captionTargetId-1="figure-194@2.[155,1432,489,1762]" captionTargetPageId-0="1" captionTargetPageId-1="2" captionText-0="FIGURES 1–3. 1. Ctenagenia vespiformis ♀ dark colour pattern, body length 19.5 mm; 2.Ctenagenia vespiformis ♀ usual coulour pattern, boldy length 20.0 mm; 3. Ctenagenia wahisi ♀ holotype, body length 20.0 mm." captionText-1="FIGURES 4–9. 4–8. Ctenagenia wahisi;4. ♂, body length 11.5 mm; 5. ♀ face; 6. ♀ ocelli; 7. ♀ tarsus of right foreleg; 8. ♂ S8; 9. Ctenagenia vespiformis ♂ S8." figureDoi-0="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6637293" figureDoi-1="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6637297" httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/6637293/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/6637297/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="94">Figs 3–4</figureCitation>
). In 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Wahis" authorityYear="2002" box="[1331,1437,1984,2011]" class="Insecta" family="Pompilidae" genus="Ctenagenia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="94" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ozbeki">
<emphasis box="[1331,1437,1984,2011]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="94">C. ozbeki</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Klug" baseAuthorityYear="1834" box="[200,364,151,177]" class="Insecta" family="Pompilidae" genus="Ctenagenia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="95" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vespiformis">
C. 
<emphasis box="[235,364,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="95">vespiformis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
T1 is black or red (
<figureCitation box="[594,694,151,177]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–3" captionStartId="1.[151,264,1590,1614]" captionTargetBox="[154,1432,919,1564]" captionTargetId="figure-317@1.[154,1432,919,1564]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1–3. 1. Ctenagenia vespiformis ♀ dark colour pattern, body length 19.5 mm; 2.Ctenagenia vespiformis ♀ usual coulour pattern, boldy length 20.0 mm; 3. Ctenagenia wahisi ♀ holotype, body length 20.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6637293" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6637293/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="95">Figs 1–2</figureCitation>
) (with a very small spot on some 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Klug" baseAuthorityYear="1834" box="[1090,1253,151,177]" class="Insecta" family="Pompilidae" genus="Ctenagenia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="95" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vespiformis">
<emphasis box="[1090,1253,151,177]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="95">C. vespiformis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
males), and the mesosoma and abdomen are all yellow with some pale red in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schmid-Egger" authorityYear="2019" box="[853,987,187,213]" class="Insecta" family="Pompilidae" genus="Ctenagenia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="95" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pagliano">
<emphasis box="[853,987,187,213]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="95">C. pagliano</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
female. The male of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schmid-Egger" authorityYear="2019" box="[1231,1364,187,213]" class="Insecta" family="Pompilidae" genus="Ctenagenia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="95" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pagliano">
<emphasis box="[1231,1364,187,213]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="95">C. pagliano</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is undescribed. Also, the setae of the head and propodeum are shorter and more sparse in 
<taxonomicName authority="Schmid-Egger, 2022" authorityName="Schmid-Egger" authorityYear="2022" box="[1127,1234,223,249]" class="Insecta" family="Pompilidae" genus="Ctenagenia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="95" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="wahisi" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1127,1234,223,249]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="95">C. wahisi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1243,1335,223,249]" pageId="2" pageNumber="95">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1243,1335,223,249]" pageId="2" pageNumber="95" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[1352,1422,223,250]" captionStart="FIGURES 4–9" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1786,1810]" captionTargetBox="[158,1432,490,1762]" captionTargetId="figure-194@2.[155,1432,489,1762]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 4–9. 4–8. Ctenagenia wahisi;4. ♂, body length 11.5 mm; 5. ♀ face; 6. ♀ ocelli; 7. ♀ tarsus of right foreleg; 8. ♂ S8; 9. Ctenagenia vespiformis ♂ S8." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6637297" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6637297/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="95">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
), compared to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Klug" baseAuthorityYear="1834" box="[302,466,259,285]" class="Insecta" family="Pompilidae" genus="Ctenagenia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="95" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vespiformis">
<emphasis box="[302,466,259,285]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="95">C. vespiformis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The foremetatarsus of the female has five spines in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Klug" baseAuthorityYear="1834" box="[1080,1244,259,285]" class="Insecta" family="Pompilidae" genus="Ctenagenia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="95" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vespiformis">
<emphasis box="[1080,1244,259,285]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="95">C. vespiformis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and four spines in the other species, including 
<taxonomicName authority="Schmid-Egger, 2022" authorityName="Schmid-Egger" authorityYear="2022" box="[500,606,295,321]" class="Insecta" family="Pompilidae" genus="Ctenagenia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="95" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="wahisi" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[500,606,295,321]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="95">C. wahisi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[615,706,295,321]" pageId="2" pageNumber="95">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[615,706,295,321]" pageId="2" pageNumber="95" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[722,792,295,321]" captionStart="FIGURES 4–9" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1786,1810]" captionTargetBox="[158,1432,490,1762]" captionTargetId="figure-194@2.[155,1432,489,1762]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 4–9. 4–8. Ctenagenia wahisi;4. ♂, body length 11.5 mm; 5. ♀ face; 6. ♀ ocelli; 7. ♀ tarsus of right foreleg; 8. ♂ S8; 9. Ctenagenia vespiformis ♂ S8." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6637297" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6637297/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="95">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
). The ocelli of 
<taxonomicName authority="Schmid-Egger, 2022" authorityName="Schmid-Egger" authorityYear="2022" box="[968,1075,295,321]" class="Insecta" family="Pompilidae" genus="Ctenagenia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="95" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="wahisi" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[968,1075,295,321]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="95">C. wahisi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1083,1174,295,321]" pageId="2" pageNumber="95">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1083,1174,295,321]" pageId="2" pageNumber="95" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
are smaller than in the remaining species (
<figureCitation box="[368,437,331,358]" captionStart="FIGURES 4–9" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1786,1810]" captionTargetBox="[158,1432,490,1762]" captionTargetId="figure-194@2.[155,1432,489,1762]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 4–9. 4–8. Ctenagenia wahisi;4. ♂, body length 11.5 mm; 5. ♀ face; 6. ♀ ocelli; 7. ♀ tarsus of right foreleg; 8. ♂ S8; 9. Ctenagenia vespiformis ♂ S8." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6637297" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6637297/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="95">Fig. 6</figureCitation>
), and the propodeal surface is more finely sculptured than in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Klug" baseAuthorityYear="1834" box="[1125,1287,331,357]" class="Insecta" family="Pompilidae" genus="Ctenagenia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="95" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vespiformis">
<emphasis box="[1125,1287,331,357]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="95">C. vespiformis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The male of 
<taxonomicName authority="Schmid-Egger, 2022" authorityName="Schmid-Egger" authorityYear="2022" box="[151,257,367,393]" class="Insecta" family="Pompilidae" genus="Ctenagenia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="95" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="wahisi" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[151,257,367,393]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="95">C. wahisi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[265,355,367,393]" pageId="2" pageNumber="95">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[265,355,367,393]" pageId="2" pageNumber="95" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
is also characterized by having a higher and more rounded keel of S8 (seen in lateral view, 
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 4–9" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1786,1810]" captionTargetBox="[158,1432,490,1762]" captionTargetId="figure-194@2.[155,1432,489,1762]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 4–9. 4–8. Ctenagenia wahisi;4. ♂, body length 11.5 mm; 5. ♀ face; 6. ♀ ocelli; 7. ♀ tarsus of right foreleg; 8. ♂ S8; 9. Ctenagenia vespiformis ♂ S8." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6637297" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6637297/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="95">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
), compared to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Klug" baseAuthorityYear="1834" box="[338,501,403,429]" class="Insecta" family="Pompilidae" genus="Ctenagenia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="95" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vespiformis">
<emphasis box="[338,501,403,429]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="95">C. vespiformis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[518,587,403,429]" captionStart="FIGURES 4–9" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1786,1810]" captionTargetBox="[158,1432,490,1762]" captionTargetId="figure-194@2.[155,1432,489,1762]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 4–9. 4–8. Ctenagenia wahisi;4. ♂, body length 11.5 mm; 5. ♀ face; 6. ♀ ocelli; 7. ♀ tarsus of right foreleg; 8. ♂ S8; 9. Ctenagenia vespiformis ♂ S8." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6637297" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6637297/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="95">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
). T1 is predominantly yellow, and all black or at most with a small medial yellow spot in 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Klug" baseAuthorityYear="1834" box="[317,472,439,465]" class="Insecta" family="Pompilidae" genus="Ctenagenia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="95" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vespiformis">
<emphasis box="[317,472,439,465]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="95">C.vespiformis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6637297" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6637297" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6637297/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="95" startId="2.[151,264,1786,1810]" targetBox="[158,1432,490,1762]" targetPageId="2">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1436,1786,1848]" pageId="2" pageNumber="95">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,314,1786,1810]" pageId="2" pageNumber="95">FIGURES 4–9.</emphasis>
4–8. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schmid-Egger" authorityYear="2022" box="[370,559,1786,1810]" class="Insecta" family="Pompilidae" genus="Ctenagenia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="95" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="wahisi">
<emphasis box="[370,559,1786,1810]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="95">Ctenagenia wahisi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
;4. ♂, body length 11.5 mm; 5. ♀ face; 6. ♀ ocelli; 7. ♀ tarsus of right foreleg; 8. ♂ S8; 9. 
<emphasis box="[177,442,1822,1848]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="95">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Klug" baseAuthorityYear="1834" box="[177,417,1822,1846]" class="Insecta" family="Pompilidae" genus="Ctenagenia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="95" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vespiformis">Ctenagenia vespiformis</taxonomicName>
♂
</emphasis>
S8.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<subSubSection lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="96" pageId="2" pageNumber="95" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="2.[151,1437,1892,2027]" lastBlockId="3.[151,1437,151,897]" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="96" pageId="2" pageNumber="95">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,574,1892,1918]" pageId="2" pageNumber="95">
Description of female 
<typeStatus box="[464,569,1892,1918]" pageId="2" pageNumber="95">holotype</typeStatus>
.
</emphasis>
Body length 20.0 mm. Colour. Black, with the following parts dark yellow: T1 with large rectangular median spot, T2 except large dark lateral margin, T3–6 completely, with darker lateral margins. S3–6 yellowish brown (
<figureCitation box="[527,597,1964,1990]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–3" captionStartId="1.[151,264,1590,1614]" captionTargetBox="[154,1432,919,1564]" captionTargetId="figure-317@1.[154,1432,919,1564]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1–3. 1. Ctenagenia vespiformis ♀ dark colour pattern, body length 19.5 mm; 2.Ctenagenia vespiformis ♀ usual coulour pattern, boldy length 20.0 mm; 3. Ctenagenia wahisi ♀ holotype, body length 20.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6637293" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6637293/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="95">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
). Face, foreleg, metapostnotum and base of S2 with distinct red shimmer. Wing base black, wings yellowish, extreme apex of forewing dark. Wing venation in apical half of wing brown, in basal half yellow. Morphology. Labrum large, apicomedially with small impression. Clypeus clearly bulged medially, ACM nearly straight (
<figureCitation box="[458,529,186,213]" captionStart="FIGURES 4–9" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1786,1810]" captionTargetBox="[158,1432,490,1762]" captionTargetId="figure-194@2.[155,1432,489,1762]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 4–9. 4–8. Ctenagenia wahisi;4. ♂, body length 11.5 mm; 5. ♀ face; 6. ♀ ocelli; 7. ♀ tarsus of right foreleg; 8. ♂ S8; 9. Ctenagenia vespiformis ♂ S8." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6637297" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6637297/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="96">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
). Ocelli and proportions of vertex see 
<figureCitation box="[972,1041,187,213]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–3" captionStartId="1.[151,264,1590,1614]" captionTargetBox="[154,1432,919,1564]" captionTargetId="figure-317@1.[154,1432,919,1564]" captionTargetPageId="1" captionText="FIGURES 1–3. 1. Ctenagenia vespiformis ♀ dark colour pattern, body length 19.5 mm; 2.Ctenagenia vespiformis ♀ usual coulour pattern, boldy length 20.0 mm; 3. Ctenagenia wahisi ♀ holotype, body length 20.0 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6637293" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6637293/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="96">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
. Head below and prosternum with many short, black bristles. Antenna long and slender, 
<collectingCountry box="[755,792,223,249]" name="American Samoa" pageId="3" pageNumber="96">AS</collectingCountry>
3 as long as foremetatarsus. Hind margin of mesopleuron along metapleuron and propodeum with furrow, „gridded“ by small stripes. Horizontal propodeal surface short, 1/3 as long as whole length of propodeum. Metapostnotum deeply recessed between metanotum and propodeum, medially as large as midocellar diameter. Propodeal declivity slightly concave. Propodeum with fine, velvet-like surface, laterally with few dark setae, somewhat shorter than medial diameter of 
<collectingCountry box="[962,1002,367,393]" name="American Samoa" pageId="3" pageNumber="96">AS</collectingCountry>
3. Forebasitarsus with four spines (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 4–9" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1786,1810]" captionTargetBox="[158,1432,490,1762]" captionTargetId="figure-194@2.[155,1432,489,1762]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 4–9. 4–8. Ctenagenia wahisi;4. ♂, body length 11.5 mm; 5. ♀ face; 6. ♀ ocelli; 7. ♀ tarsus of right foreleg; 8. ♂ S8; 9. Ctenagenia vespiformis ♂ S8." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6637297" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6637297/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="96">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
). Legs asetose, except with few very short setae on upper side of femora. T6 with few and S6 with many long black bristles.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,151,897]" pageId="3" pageNumber="96">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,549,474,501]" pageId="3" pageNumber="96">
Variation in female 
<typeStatus box="[434,543,475,501]" pageId="3" pageNumber="96">paratype</typeStatus>
.
</emphasis>
The female 
<typeStatus box="[688,784,475,501]" pageId="3" pageNumber="96">paratype</typeStatus>
is distinctly smaller than the 
<typeStatus box="[1112,1210,475,501]" pageId="3" pageNumber="96">holotype</typeStatus>
(16.0 mm), the face and antenna are more reddish (antenna partly orange reddish), and the horizontal part of the propodeum is longer than in 
<typeStatus box="[235,333,547,573]" pageId="3" pageNumber="96">holotype</typeStatus>
(ca. 50% of propodeal length).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,151,897]" pageId="3" pageNumber="96">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,550,582,609]" pageId="3" pageNumber="96">
Description of male 
<typeStatus box="[436,545,583,609]" pageId="3" pageNumber="96">paratype</typeStatus>
.
</emphasis>
Body length 
<quantity box="[699,800,582,609]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.15" pageId="3" pageNumber="96" unit="mm" value="11.5">11.5 mm</quantity>
. Agrees in colour pattern and general aspects of morphology with the female (
<figureCitation box="[390,459,619,645]" captionStart="FIGURES 4–9" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1786,1810]" captionTargetBox="[158,1432,490,1762]" captionTargetId="figure-194@2.[155,1432,489,1762]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 4–9. 4–8. Ctenagenia wahisi;4. ♂, body length 11.5 mm; 5. ♀ face; 6. ♀ ocelli; 7. ♀ tarsus of right foreleg; 8. ♂ S8; 9. Ctenagenia vespiformis ♂ S8." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6637297" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6637297/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="96">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
), with the following exceptions: face and antenna black with light reddish shimmer (as in female 
<typeStatus box="[261,362,655,681]" pageId="3" pageNumber="96">paratype</typeStatus>
), inner eye margin with some orange-yellow markings. Pronotum, mesopleuron and mesoscutum with reddish shimmer. T1 all yellow except base and lateral parts of T1. Metapostnotum narrow, medially half long as midocellar diameter. Horizontal part of propodeum 2/3 as long as whole propodeum. S8 with high keel, in lateral view with apex distinctly rounded (
<figureCitation box="[548,616,763,789]" captionStart="FIGURES 4–9" captionStartId="2.[151,264,1786,1810]" captionTargetBox="[158,1432,490,1762]" captionTargetId="figure-194@2.[155,1432,489,1762]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 4–9. 4–8. Ctenagenia wahisi;4. ♂, body length 11.5 mm; 5. ♀ face; 6. ♀ ocelli; 7. ♀ tarsus of right foreleg; 8. ♂ S8; 9. Ctenagenia vespiformis ♂ S8." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6637297" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6637297/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="96">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection box="[199,733,798,825]" pageId="3" pageNumber="96" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,151,897]" box="[199,733,798,825]" pageId="3" pageNumber="96">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,353,798,824]" pageId="3" pageNumber="96">Distribution.</emphasis>
<collectingRegion box="[359,518,799,825]" country="Oman" name="Zufar" pageId="3" pageNumber="96">Dhofar region</collectingRegion>
in southern 
<collectingCountry box="[656,728,799,825]" name="Oman" pageId="3" pageNumber="96">Oman</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="96" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,151,897]" pageId="3" pageNumber="96">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,334,835,861]" pageId="3" pageNumber="96">Etymology.</emphasis>
The species is named in honour to the late Raymond Wahis, an outstanding expert of 
<taxonomicName box="[1309,1437,835,861]" class="Insecta" family="Pompilidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="96" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Pompilidae</taxonomicName>
and friend. He influenced the work of the author significantly.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
</treatment>
